dspResourceId.name: dspResourceId
dspResourceId.description: DSP resource type enumerations. The algoSets describe the mode of the DSP card. Each mode corresponds to a set of algorithms supported by the IO card. Aal modes describe the aal type used. algoSet1-aal2-non-multiplexed: resource type for algoSet1 DSP mode and non-multiplexed aal2 AAL mode. algoSet1-aal2-std : resource type for algoSet1 DSP mode and standard aal2 AAL mode. algoSet2-aal2-non-multiplexed: resource type for algoSet2 DSP mode and non-multiplexed aal2 AAL mode.aal2 AAL mode. algoSet2-aal2-std: resource type for algoSet2 DSP mode and standard aal2 AAL mode. algoSet3-aal2-non-multiplexed: resource type for algoSet3 DSP mode and non-multiplexed aal2 AAL mode. algoSet3-aal2-std: resource type for algoSet3 DSP mode and standard aal2 AAL mode. algoSet5-aal1: resource type for algoSet5 DSP mode and aal1 AAL mode. algoSet6-aal2-std: resource type for algoSet6 DSP mode and standard aal2 AAL mode. tone-annce-cas: resource type for the tone announcement interface and CAS mode of the TASM card. tone-annce-tas: resource type for the tone announcement interface and TAS mode of the TASM card.

dspResourceAvail.name: dspResourceAvail
dspResourceAvail.description: The available DSP resource counts how many connections can be made using this available DSP resource type in the system.

dspResourceUsed.name: dspResourceUsed
dspResourceUsed.description: The used DSP resource counts how many connections are already made using this available DSP resource type in the system.

dspResourceUsedFailed.name: dspResourceUsedFailed
dspResourceUsedFailed.description: The used but failed DSP resource counts how many connections are already made using currently failed DSP resource type in the system.

dspResourceAvailFailed.name: dspResourceAvailFailed

tasmMaxDigitControlBlocks.description: Specifies the maximum number of digit collection that can be initiated simultaneously. This will depend on the number of control blocks allocated for playing tones and announcements and for line tests as the memory comes from the same pool. The tasmControlBlockResAllocUsage field will be updated to indicate this .

tasmMaxTestControlBlocks.name: tasmMaxTestControlBlocks
tasmMaxTestControlBlocks.description: Specifies the maximum number of TDM line tests that can be initiated simultaneously. This will depend on the number of control blocks allocated for playing tones and announcements and for digit collection as the memory comes from the same pool. The tasmControlBlockResAllocUsage field will be updated to indicate this.

tasmMaxMemResvd.name: tasmMaxMemResvd
tasmMaxMemResvd.description: Specifies the maximum amount of memory in megabytes reserved for TASM.

tasmControlBlockResAllocUsage.name: tasmControlBlockResAllocUsage
tasmControlBlockResAllocUsage.description: The percentage of memory usage for tones, announcements, digit collection and line tests control blocks.

tasmAnnceCacheMemResAllocUsage.name: tasmAnnceCacheMemResAllocUsage
tasmAnnceCacheMemResAllocUsage.description: The percentage of memory usage for caching announcements in memory. Everytime an announcement is compressed this field will be updated to reflect the cache memory that will be taken up by this announcement. Once this field shows a 100 percent usage it is an indication to the user that any additional announcement will cause the system to thrash as it clears an announcement in cache to make room for the new announcement.

cardProtectionStatus.description: Current protection status of the card: none if the card is un-protected; protected if it is under the protection of another card; wrongType if the card types of protection card and protected card are different.

cardOperStatus.description: Current operational status of the card. For I/O card, it is primary if configured, it is unknown if unconfigured, or removed. For CPU, it is primary if the CPU is master CPU, or standby if the CPU is slave CPU.

cardOperatingMode.name: cardOperatingMode
cardOperatingMode.description: Mode of operation for a card. This is applicable to those card types which can be configured in a dual mode. e.g. unstDS3E3-3P can be operational as either a 3 port DS3 or E3 card. All ports on the card will be of the same type depending on the card's operating mode.

protectionConfigMode.name: protectionConfigMode
protectionConfigMode.description: Protection Configuration Mode of a Card unprotected: Card is not in protection or protected state protection: Card is in protection state working: Card is in protected/working state and this state is read only and cannot be set by the user

protectionStatus.name: protectionStatus
protectionStatus.description: Protection Status of a card. Inservice and OutofService indicates if the card has failed or still operational. Active or Standby state indicates if it is carrying active traffic or not.

protectionSlot.name: protectionSlot
protectionSlot.description: If Protection Config Mode is Working then this field gives the protection slot.

taxiPortConfigTable.name: taxiPortConfigTable
taxiPortConfigTable.description: Table of common physical Port attributes

taxiPortConfigEntry.name: taxiPortConfigEntry
taxiPortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for common physical port attributes

taxiLineStatus.name: taxiLineStatus
taxiLineStatus.description: taxi line status: 1: NoAlarm 2: Loss of Signal

taxiOutputTransferRate.name: taxiOutputTransferRate
taxiOutputTransferRate.description: User selectable parameter which allows the outgoing rate of the port to be reduced to 50% taxi, halfRate, only on AQueMan.

ds3PortConfigTable.name: ds3PortConfigTable
ds3PortConfigTable.description: Table of ds3 specific port attributes

ds3PortConfigEntry.name: ds3PortConfigEntry
ds3PortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for ds3 specific port attributes

ds3LineType.name: ds3LineType
ds3LineType.description: This variable indicates the variety of DS3 C-bit implementing this interface. The type of interface affects the interpretation of the usage and error statistics. The rate of DS3 is 44.736 Mbps. The dsx3ClearChannel value means that the C-bits are not used except for sending/receiving AIS. The values, in sequence, describe: TITLE: SPECIFICATION: dsx3CbitParity ANSI T1.107a-1989 dsx3ClearChannel ANSI T1.102-1987.

ds3LineCoding.name: ds3LineCoding
ds3LineCoding.description: This variable describes the variety of Zero Code Suppression used on this interface, which in turn affects a number of its characteristics. ds3B3ZS refers to the use of specified patterns of normal bits and bipolar violations which are used to replace sequences of zero bits of a specified length.

ds3LoopbackConfig.name: ds3LoopbackConfig
ds3LoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the DS3 interface. See above diagrams for explanations of loops.

ds3TransmitClockSource.name: ds3TransmitClockSource
ds3TransmitClockSource.description: The source of Tranmit Clock. 'loopTiming' indicates that the recovered re- ceive clock is used as the transmit clock. 'localTiming' indicates that a local clock source is used. 'cardFreeRun' indicates that a local oscillator on the I/O card is used as the transmit clock. 'adaptiveTiming' indicates that the adaptive clocking mechanism is used

ds3LineStatus.name: ds3LineStatus
ds3LineStatus.description: ds3 line status: 1: dsx3NoAlarm: No alarm present 2: dsx3RcvRAIFailure: Receiving Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 4: dsx3XmitRAIAlarm: Transmitting Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 8: dsx3RcvAIS: Receiving AIS failure state 16: dsx3XmitAIS: Transmitting AIS failure statue 32: dsx3LOF: Receiving LOF failure state 64: dsx3LOS: Reveiving LOS failure state 128: dsx3LoopbackState: Looping the received signal 256: dsx3RcvTestCode: Receiving a Test Pattern 512: dsx3OtherFailure: any line status not defined 1024: dsx3RcvRmtAIS: 2048: dsx3RcvRmtOOF: 4096: dsx3RcvRmtLOS: 8192: dsx3RcvRmtIdle: 16384: dsx3RmtLoopback: Far end remote loopback

ds3SendCode.name: ds3SendCode
ds3SendCode.description: This variable indicates what type of code is being sent across the ds3 interface by the device. The values mean: 'noCode' - sending looped or normal data 'lineLoopCode' - sending a request for a line loopback 'deactivateCode' - sending a loopback deactivation request 'testPattern' - sending a test pattern

ds3OutputTxRate.name: ds3OutputTxRate
ds3OutputTxRate.description: The ability to adjust the bandwidth of DS3 in tx direction. The adjustable DS3 bandwidth will support 1% increments.

msPortConfigTable.name: msPortConfigTable
msPortConfigTable.description: Table of multi-serial card's port attributes

msPortConfigEntry.name: msPortConfigEntry
msPortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for multi-serial port attributes

msBaudRate.name: msBaudRate
msBaudRate.description: baud rate is determined by multiplying this number by the msBaudRateMultiplier

msRs232XmitMode.name: msRs232XmitMode
msRs232XmitMode.description: transmit mode for rs232 DTE/DCE serial port

msRs232Parity.name: msRs232Parity
msRs232Parity.description: parity for rs232 DTE/DCE serial port

msRs232DataBits.name: msRs232DataBits
msRs232DataBits.description: data bits for rs232 DTE/DCE serial port

msRs232StopBits.name: msRs232StopBits
msRs232StopBits.description: stop bits for rs232 DTE/DCE serial port

msTxDataClkSrcForDte.name: msTxDataClkSrcForDte
msTxDataClkSrcForDte.description: Transmit data clock source for DTE, externalTx in is not valid for rs232. This field is ignored if the local side is DCE.

msTxDataClkSrcForDce.name: msTxDataClkSrcForDce
msTxDataClkSrcForDce.description: Transmit data clock source for DCE localTiming: a local clock source is used. (e.g., from backplane (stratum) loopTiming: from remote This field is ignored if the local side is DTE

msRxDataClkSrcForDce.name: msRxDataClkSrcForDce
msRxDataClkSrcForDce.description: Receive data clock source for DCE localTiming: a local clock source is used. (e.g., from backplane (stratum) loopTiming: from remote This field is ignored if the local side is DTE

msRxClkPolarity.name: msRxClkPolarity
msRxClkPolarity.description: Whether or not to reverse the receive clock

msTxClkPolarity.name: msTxClkPolarity
msTxClkPolarity.description: Whether or not to reverse the transmit clock

msHandshake.name: msHandshake
msHandshake.description: Multiserial Module handshake: observed : used with AAL1 to monitor RTS/CTS exchange.

msSpeedAdaption.name: msSpeedAdaption
msSpeedAdaption.description: The state of allowing speed adaption

msBitStuffing.name: msBitStuffing
msBitStuffing.description: When msBitStuffing is enabled, CAC throughput is (1 + 1/7) user throughtput. Otherwise the CAC throughput is the same as the user throughput. msBitStuffing can only be enabled for circuit emulation interfaces.

msLineStatus.name: msLineStatus
msLineStatus.description: line status on the port: The msLineStatus is a bit map representation. It can represent multiple failures (alarms) if supported by the card. NoAlarm should be set if and only if no other flag is set. The various bit positions are: 1: NoAlarm 2: Loss of Signal

msRxDataPolarity.name: msRxDataPolarity
msRxDataPolarity.description: Whether or not to reverse the receive data

msTxDataPolarity.name: msTxDataPolarity
msTxDataPolarity.description: Whether or not to reverse the transmit data

msLoopbackConfig.name: msLoopbackConfig
msLoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the Serial port.

msLOSDetection.name: msLOSDetection
msLOSDetection.description: State of detection of LOS by IO card. LOS detection is always enabled when msBitStuffing is enabled. When the interface is not circuit emulation, the IO card does not report any LOS.

ds1PortConfigTable.name: ds1PortConfigTable
ds1PortConfigTable.description: Table of ds1 specific port attributes

ds1PortConfigEntry.name: ds1PortConfigEntry
ds1PortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for ds1 specific port attributes

ds1LoopbackConfig.name: ds1LoopbackConfig
ds1LoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the ds1 interface

ds1LineStatus.name: ds1LineStatus
ds1LineStatus.description: This variable indicates the Line Status of the interface. It contains loopback, failure, re- ceived 'alarm' and transmitted 'alarm' infor- mation. The dsx1LineStatus is a bit map represented as a sum, therefore, it can represent multiple failures (alarms) and a LoopbackState simultaneously. ds1NoAlarm should be set if and only if no other flag is set. If the ds1LoopbackState bit is set, the loopbak in effect can be determined from the ds1LoopbackConfig object. The various bit positions are: 1: dsx1NoAlarm: No Alarm Present 2: dsx1RcvFarEndLOF: Far end LOF (a.k.a., Yellow Alarm) 4: dsx1XmtFarEndLOF: Near end sending LOF Indication 8: dsx1RcvAIS: Far end sending AIS 16: dsx1XmtAIS: Near end sending AIS 32: dsx1LossOfFrame: Near end LOF (a.k.a., Red Alarm) 64: dsx1LossOfSignal: Near end Loss Of Signal 128: dsx1LoopbackState: Near end is looped 256: dsx1T16AIS: E1 TS16 AIS 512: dsx1RcvFarEndLOMF: Far End Sending TS16 LOMF 1024: dsx1XmtFarEndLOMF: Near End Sending TS16 LOMF 2048: dsx1RcvTestCode: Near End detects a test code 4096: dsx1OtherFailure: any line status not defined here 8192: dsx1RmtLoopback: Far end loopback

ds1EnhanceFeatureSet1.name: ds1EnhanceFeatureSet1
ds1EnhanceFeatureSet1.description: To enable/disable a proprietary ab signaling scheme, it applies to all DS0s in the port. No individual DS0 signaling can be configured under this scheme.

ds1DataTransferType.name: ds1DataTransferType
ds1DataTransferType.description: DS1 data transfer type is only applicable in Circuit Emulation where unstructured CE packets entire T1 frame including the F-bit into the AAL1 for data tranfer, whereas, the structured CE packets the entire T1 frame except the F-bit.

ds1OamInterworkingType.name: ds1OamInterworkingType
ds1OamInterworkingType.description: Specifies whether the interworking is done by trunk conditioning or unframed1s

ds1InLineCode.name: ds1InLineCode
ds1InLineCode.description: To select and support the inlinecode option in either ANSI or DS1_ANI (ANI: Access Network Interface)

oc3PortConfigTable.description: Table of common physical Port attributes

oc3PortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for common physical port attributes

oc3LoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the OC3 interface See above diagrams for explanations of loops.

oc3TransmitClockSource.name: oc3TransmitClockSource
oc3TransmitClockSource.description: The source of Tranmit Clock. 'loopTiming' indicates that the recovered re- ceive clock is used as the transmit clock. 'localTiming' indicates that a local clock source is used.

oc3LineStatus.name: oc3LineStatus
oc3LineStatus.description: oc3 line status - 1: oc3NoAlarm: No alarm present 2: oc3RcvRAIFailure: Receiving Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 4: oc3XmitRAIAlarm: Transmitting Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 8: oc3RcvAIS: Receiving AIS failure state 16: oc3XmitAIS: Transmitting AIS failure statue 32: oc3LOF: Receiving LOF failure state 64: oc3LOS: Reveiving LOS failure state 128: oc3LoopbackState: Looping the received signal 256: oc3RcvTestCode: Receiving a Test Pattern 512: oc3OtherFailure: any line status not defined 1024: oc3LCD: Receiving Loss Of Cell Delineation 2048: oc3LRDI: Receiving Line RDI failure state 4096: oc3PRDI: Receiving Path RDI failure state

oc3OutputTransferRate.name: oc3OutputTransferRate

oc3APSConfiguration.name: oc3APSConfiguration
oc3APSConfiguration.description: Indicates whether APS is configured for this port .

oc3APSPairConfigTable.name: oc3APSPairConfigTable
oc3APSPairConfigTable.description: Table of common physical Port attributes

oc3APSPairConfigEntry.name: oc3APSPairConfigEntry
oc3APSPairConfigEntry.description: Row definition for common physical port attributes

oc3APSPairMode.name: oc3APSPairMode
oc3APSPairMode.description: Unidirectional or Bidirectional mode: Uni - Each pair operates independently i.e. a switch over in one pair does not effect the remote pair. Bi - both remote and local pairs have to switch together.

oc3APSPairOption.name: oc3APSPairOption
oc3APSPairOption.description: Nonrevertive - After a switch to Prot port, even if the working comes up there is no switch to the working port back. Revertive - traffic is switched back to work port after it comes back.

oc3APSPairWorkingSFBERThreshold.name: oc3APSPairWorkingSFBERThreshold
oc3APSPairWorkingSFBERThreshold.description: Bits error Rate threshold to declare signal failure

oc3APSPairProtectionSFBERThreshold.name: oc3APSPairProtectionSFBERThreshold
oc3APSPairProtectionSFBERThreshold.description: Bits error Rate threshold to declare signal failure

oc3APSPairWorkingSDBERThreshold.name: oc3APSPairWorkingSDBERThreshold
oc3APSPairWorkingSDBERThreshold.description: Bits error Rate threshold to declare signal degrade

oc3APSPairProtectionSDBERThreshold.name: oc3APSPairProtectionSDBERThreshold
oc3APSPairProtectionSDBERThreshold.description: Bits error Rate threshold to declare signal degrade

oc3APSPairWTRPeriod.name: oc3APSPairWTRPeriod
oc3APSPairWTRPeriod.description: Duration for Wait To Restore Period between 5 to 12 minutes. Ref: BellCore GR-253-Core, Issue 3, page 200, R5-56.

oc3APSPairStatus.name: oc3APSPairStatus
oc3APSPairStatus.description: noFailure : The protection line is not in use. modeMismatch : one end is configured unidirectional and the other is bidirectional (both the ends should be configured in the same mode). Also when one end is configured for 1:1 architechture and the other end indicates it is configured for 1:n architechture.(Bidirectional mode only) swByteFailure: protection switching byte failure - defect declared when invalid / persistantly unacceptable codes are received in the K1 byte. failure declared if defect persists for an extended period. Invalid code is when the incoming K1 byte contains an unused code or a code irrelevant for the specific switching operation.(Only in bi-directional mode) chMismatch : channel mismatch is declared when the channel numbers in the transmitted K1 byte and the received K2 byte do not match for 50 ms.Channel mismatch is monitored only in bidirectional mode.

oc3APSPairCurrentState.name: oc3APSPairCurrentState
oc3APSPairCurrentState.description: Current State of the APS state machine

oc3APSPairWorkingLineSignalStatus.name: oc3APSPairWorkingLineSignalStatus
oc3APSPairWorkingLineSignalStatus.description: Signal Status of the working port (LOS / LOF / LCD / AIS etc.)

oc3APSPairProtectionLineSignalStatus.name: oc3APSPairProtectionLineSignalStatus
oc3APSPairProtectionLineSignalStatus.description: Signal Status of the protection port (LOS / LOF / LCD / AIS etc.)

oc3APSPairWorkingSDDuration.name: oc3APSPairWorkingSDDuration
oc3APSPairWorkingSDDuration.description: Duration in seconds for which the Work port has been in Signal Degradation state

oc3APSPairProtectionSFDuration.name: oc3APSPairProtectionSFDuration
oc3APSPairProtectionSFDuration.description: Duration in seconds for which the Prot port has been in Signal Failure state

oc3APSPairProtectionSDDuration.name: oc3APSPairProtectionSDDuration
oc3APSPairProtectionSDDuration.description: Duration in seconds for which the Prot port has been in Signal Degradation state

oc3APSPairTransmitK1K2Bytes.name: oc3APSPairTransmitK1K2Bytes
oc3APSPairTransmitK1K2Bytes.description: The k1 / k2 bytes being transmitted by the prot port to the remote port.

oc3APSPairReceiveK1K2Bytes.name: oc3APSPairReceiveK1K2Bytes
oc3APSPairReceiveK1K2Bytes.description: k1 / k2 bytes from the received SONET header on the protection port. k1 / k2 are used for the APS communication protocol.

oc3APSPairSwitchOverCount.name: oc3APSPairSwitchOverCount
oc3APSPairSwitchOverCount.description: Number of times the APS pair has switched over since last configuration.

e3PortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for e3 specific port attributes

e3LineType.name: e3LineType
e3LineType.description: This variable indicates the basic frame structure supported in this E3 port. The rate of E3 is 34.368 Mbps. TITLE: SPECIFICATION: G.832 ITU-T G.832 1993. G.751 ITU-T G.751 1998

e3LineCoding.name: e3LineCoding
e3LineCoding.description: The line code supported for the E3 port. The High Density Bipolar of order 3 (hdb3) as specified in section 8.1 of ITU-T G.703.

e3LoopbackConfig.name: e3LoopbackConfig
e3LoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the E3 interface. See above diagrams for explanations of loops.

e3LineStatus.name: e3LineStatus
e3LineStatus.description: e3 line status: 1: e3NoAlarm: No alarm present 2: e3RcvRAIFailure: Receiving Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 4: e3XmitRAIAlarm: Transmitting Yellow/Remote Alarm Indication 8: e3RcvAIS: Receiving AIS failure state 16: e3XmitAIS: Transmitting AIS failure statue 32: e3LOF: Receiving LOF failure state 64: e3LOS: Reveiving LOS failure state 128: e3LoopbackState: Looping the received signal 256: e3RcvTestCode: Receiving a Test Pattern 512: e3OtherFailure: any line status not defined

e1PortConfigTable.description: Table of e1 specific port attributes

e1PortConfigEntry.name: e1PortConfigEntry
e1PortConfigEntry.description: Row definition for e1 specific port attributes

e1LineType.name: e1LineType
e1LineType.description: E1 interface type. The rate of E1 is 2.048 Mbps

e1LoopbackConfig.name: e1LoopbackConfig
e1LoopbackConfig.description: This variable represents the loopback configuration of the e1 interface See above diagrams for explanations of loops.

e1LineStatus.name: e1LineStatus
e1LineStatus.description: This variable indicates the Line Status of the interface. It contains loopback, failure, re- ceived 'alarm' and transmitted 'alarm' infor- mation. The e1LineStatus is a bit map represented as a sum, therefore, it can represent multiple failures (alarms) and a LoopbackState simultaneously. e1NoAlarm should be set if and only if no other flag is set. If the e1LoopbackState bit is set, the loopback in effect can be determined from the e1LoopbackConfig object. The various bit positions are: 1: e1NoAlarm: No Alarm Present 2: e1RcvFarEndLOF: Far end LOF (a.k.a., Yellow Alarm) 4: e1XmtFarEndLOF: Near end sending LOF Indication 8: e1RcvAIS: Far end sending AIS 16: e1XmtAIS: Near end sending AIS 32: e1LossOfFrame: Near end LOF (a.k.a., Red Alarm) 64: e1LossOfSignal: Near end Loss Of Signal 128: e1LoopbackState: Near end is looped 256: e1T16AIS: E1 TS16 AIS 512: e1RcvFarEndLOMF: Far End Sending TS16 LOMF 1024: e1XmtFarEndLOMF: Near End Sending TS16 LOMF 2048: e1RcvTestCode: Near End detects a test code 4096: e1OtherFailure: any line status not defined here

e1TS16.name: e1TS16
e1TS16.description: Time slot 16 is configurable for channel associated signaling (CAS) or data. cas: 'ABCD' signaling will be extracted in time slot 16 if channel is configured for circuit emulation. ccs: time slot 16 will not carry any e1 channel signaling information, instead, it will be used for data.

e1DataTransferType.name: e1DataTransferType
e1DataTransferType.description: E1 data transfer type is only applicable in Circuit Emulation where unstructured CE packets entire T1 frame including the F-bit into the AAL1 for data tranfer, whereas, the structured CE packets the entire E1 frame except the Frame alignment signal channel.

e1CRC4.name: e1CRC4
e1CRC4.description: Enable or disable transmission of CRC4 bits on bit 1 of each frame.

e1OamInterworkingType.name: e1OamInterworkingType
e1OamInterworkingType.description: Specifies whether the interworking is done by trunk conditioning or unframed1s

e1EnhanceFeatureSet1.name: e1EnhanceFeatureSet1
e1EnhanceFeatureSet1.description: To enable/disable a proprietary ab signaling scheme, it applies to all DS0s in the port. No individual DS0 signaling can be configured under the scheme.

It is recommended that this be the numerically smallest MAC address of all ports that belong to this bridge. However it is only required to be unique. When concatenated with dot1dSprPriority a unique Bridgeidentifier is formed which is used in the Spanning Tree Protocol.

protectionCommand.name: protectionCommand
protectionCommand.description: List of commands which can be executed on a protection Group. Clear : This command is used to clear any previous commands which may have been and get back to normal nto1 operation Forced SwitchOver To Protection : Switchover to Protection card even if the working card is in service active These commands to used in conjunction with the working slot id.

protectionCommandSlotId.name: protectionCommandSlotId
protectionCommandSlotId.description: This is the working Slot to which command has to be applied

protectionGroupStatus.name: protectionGroupStatus
protectionGroupStatus.description: Protection Status of a Protection Card. Inservice and OutofService indicates if the card has failed or still operational. Active or Standby state indicates if it is carrying active traffic or not.

workingSlotId.name: workingSlotId
workingSlotId.description: If protection group status is active, this field will give the slot which is being working. In case it is in standby mode this field will show 0

workingFailedBitmap.name: workingFailedBitmap
workingFailedBitmap.description: Gives Bitmap of the Failed Working Slots. Subset of the Working Slot Bitmap.

protectionActiveCounter.name: protectionActiveCounter
protectionActiveCounter.description: Give the Number of Times a Protection has gone to active.

protectionOOSCounter.name: protectionOOSCounter
protectionOOSCounter.description: Give the Number of Times a Protection Card has failed.

dsp2ChannelAlarmType.description: This field is a read only failure which gives the status of a dsp.When the status is dspFailure the Operational Status at the interface level will go OOS

dsp2ChannelModeConfig.name: dsp2ChannelModeConfig
dsp2ChannelModeConfig.description: This field is used to configure the mode of the DSP card. Each mode corresponds to a set of algorithms supported by the IO card. The complete list of enumerations of supported algorithms is given in the dsp2AlgorithmTable. The following description outlines the algorithms supported in each corresponding AlgoSet. algoSet1 : g168-echo-cancellation128ms algoSet2 : g726-voice-compression, g165-echo-cancellation, generic-silence-suppression, fax-modem-tone-detection, g168-echo-cancellation64ms. algoSet3 : g729a-voice-compression, g165-echo-cancellation, g729b-silence-suppression, fax-modem-tone-detection, g168-echo-cancellation64ms. algoSet4 : v17-fax-algorithm-upto-14400-bps, v29-fax-algorithm-upto-9600-bps, v27ter-fax-algorithm-upto-2400-bps, v21-fax-algorithm-upto-300-bps. algoSet5 : g168-echo-cancellation64ms. algoSet6 : g726-voice-compression, g729a-voice-compression, g729b-silence-suppression, g168-echo-cancellation64ms, v17-fax-algorithm-upto-14400-bps, v29-fax-algorithm-upto-9600-bps, v27ter-fax-algorithm-upto-2400-bps, v21-fax-algorithm-upto-300-bps.

dsp2AlgorithmTable.name: dsp2AlgorithmTable

dsp2AlgorithmEntry.name: dsp2AlgorithmEntry

imaGrpChannelConfigTable.name: imaGrpChannelConfigTable
imaGrpChannelConfigTable.description: Table used for the IMA virtual channel (group) configuration on cards that have physical interfaces configured as atmIma. Represents three channels that can be configured as IMA groups on port 7 of DS1 and E1 cards.

imaGrpChannelConfigEntry.name: imaGrpChannelConfigEntry
imaGrpChannelConfigEntry.description: Row definition for common physical port attributes

imaGrpChannelPortMap.name: imaGrpChannelPortMap
imaGrpChannelPortMap.description: A bitmap that identifies the physical IMA interfaces in this group. The least significant bit represents port 1.

imaGrpChannelNeState.name: imaGrpChannelNeState
imaGrpChannelNeState.description: The current operational state of the near-end IMA Group State Machine.

imaGrpChannelFeState.name: imaGrpChannelFeState
imaGrpChannelFeState.description: The current operational state of the far-end IMA Group State Machine.

imaGrpChannelFailureStatus.name: imaGrpChannelFailureStatus
imaGrpChannelFailureStatus.description: The current failure status of the IMA group (the reason why the GTSM is in the down state). noFailure(1) no failure startUpNe(2) near-end is in the state of start-up startUpFe(3) far-end is in the state of start-up invalidMValueNe(4) near-end has invalid frame length invalidMValueFe(5) far-end has invalid frame length failedAssymetricNe(6) near-end failed due to incompatable symmetry failedAssymetricFe(7) far-end failed due to incompatable symmetry insuffLinksNe(8) Near-end reported less than the min number of Tx links are active or less than the min number of Rx links are active insuffLinksFe(9) Far-end reported less than the min number of Rx links are active or less than thenmin number of Tx links are active blockedNe(10) Near-end is administratively out-of-service blockedFe(11) Far-end is administratively out-of-service otherFailure(12) other failures

imaGrpChannelSymmetry.name: imaGrpChannelSymmetry
imaGrpChannelSymmetry.description: Symmetry of the IMA group. Symmetric configuration: all ports of IMA group are configured as full-duplex. With symmetric configuration, operation is symmetric if no links failes; is asymmetric if a link fails so that the active forward and backward links between far-end and near-end are asymmetric. If the configuration is asymmetric, the operation can never be symmetric.

imaGrpChannelMinNumTxLinks.name: imaGrpChannelMinNumTxLinks
imaGrpChannelMinNumTxLinks.description: Minimum number of transmit links required to be Active for the IMA group to be in the Up state.

imaGrpChannelMinNumRxLinks.name: imaGrpChannelMinNumRxLinks
imaGrpChannelMinNumRxLinks.description: Minimum number of receive links required to be Active for the IMA group to be in the Up state.

imaGrpChannelNeTxClkMode.name: imaGrpChannelNeTxClkMode
imaGrpChannelNeTxClkMode.description: Transmit clocking mode used by the near-end IMA group. There are two possible modes: the Common Transmit Clock (CTC) and the Independent Transmit Clock (ITC). The CTC mode corresponds to the case when the transmit clock of all IMA links are derived from the same source. The ITC configuration corresponds to the case where there is at least one IMA link whose transmit clock is derived from a source different than at least another link transmit clock. The underlying clock configuration must be set up by the user to ensure operation in the selected mode.

imaGrpChannelFeTxClkMode.name: imaGrpChannelFeTxClkMode
imaGrpChannelFeTxClkMode.description: Transmit clocking mode used by the far-end IMA group. There are two possible modes: the Common Transmit Clock (CTC) and the Independent Transmit Clock (ITC). The CTC mode corresponds to the case when the transmit clock of all IMA links are derived from the same source. The ITC configuration corresponds to the case where there is at least one IMA link whose transmit clock is derived from a source different than at least another link transmit clock.

imaGrpChannelTxImaId.name: imaGrpChannelTxImaId
imaGrpChannelTxImaId.description: The IMA ID currently in use by the near-end IMA function.

imaGrpChannelRxImaId.name: imaGrpChannelRxImaId
imaGrpChannelRxImaId.description: The IMA ID currently in use by the far-end IMA function.

imaGrpChannelTxFrameLength.name: imaGrpChannelTxFrameLength
imaGrpChannelTxFrameLength.description: The frame length to be used by the IMA group in the transmit direction. Can only be set when the IMA group is startup.

imaGrpChannelRxFrameLength.name: imaGrpChannelRxFrameLength
imaGrpChannelRxFrameLength.description: Value of IMA frame length as received from remote IMA function.

imaGrpChannelDiffLinkDelayMax.name: imaGrpChannelDiffLinkDelayMax
imaGrpChannelDiffLinkDelayMax.description: The maximum number of milliseconds of delay differential among the links that will be tolerated on this interface.

imaGrpChannelLeastDelayLink.name: imaGrpChannelLeastDelayLink
imaGrpChannelLeastDelayLink.description: The Interface Index of the link configured in the IMA group which has the smallest link propagation delay. This value has meaning only if at least 1 link has been configured in the IMA group.

imaGrpChannelDiffDelayMaxObs.name: imaGrpChannelDiffDelayMaxObs
imaGrpChannelDiffDelayMaxObs.description: The latest maximum differential delay observed (in milliseconds), i.e. between the links having the least and most link propagation delay, among the receive links that are currently configured in the IMA group.

imaGrpChannelAlphaValue.name: imaGrpChannelAlphaValue
imaGrpChannelAlphaValue.description: This indicates the 'alpha' value used to specify the number of consecutive invalid ICP cells to be detected before moving to the IMA HUNT state.

imaGrpChannelBetaValue.name: imaGrpChannelBetaValue
imaGrpChannelBetaValue.description: This indicates the 'beta' value used to specify the number of consecutive errored ICP cells to be detected before moving to the IMA HUNT state.

imaGrpChannelGammaValue.name: imaGrpChannelGammaValue
imaGrpChannelGammaValue.description: This indicates the 'gamma' value used to specify the number of consecutive valid ICP cells to be detected before moving to the IMA SYNC state from the PRESYNC state.

imaGrpChannelStatsNeNumFailures.name: imaGrpChannelStatsNeNumFailures
imaGrpChannelStatsNeNumFailures.description: The number of times a near-end group failure (Config-Abort, Insufficient-Links) has been reported.

imaGrpChannelStatsFeNumFailures.name: imaGrpChannelStatsFeNumFailures
imaGrpChannelStatsFeNumFailures.description: The number of times a far-end group failure (Config-Abort-FE, Insufficient-Links-FE, Blocked-FE) has been reported.

imaGrpChannelStatsNumTxActLnks.name: imaGrpChannelStatsNumTxActLnks
imaGrpChannelStatsNumTxActLnks.description: The number of links which are configured to transmit and are currently Active in this IMA group.

imaGrpChannelStatsNumRxActLnks.name: imaGrpChannelStatsNumRxActLnks
imaGrpChannelStatsNumRxActLnks.description: The number of links which are configured to receive and are currently Active in this IMA group.

imaGrpChannelStatsTimer.name: imaGrpChannelStatsTimer
imaGrpChannelStatsTimer.description: Time, in seconds, since last reset.

imaGrpChannelCompatMode.name: imaGrpChannelCompatMode
imaGrpChannelCompatMode.description: This is used to indicate interoperability mode to the I/O card in terms of reporting the link status at the correct location in the IMA Control Protocol (ICP) cell

tasmChannelModeConfig.name: tasmChannelModeConfig

The modes are explained as follows: casMode: DSP resource is used for DTMF/MF tone detection/generation and running the Type 100, 105, and 108 tests. tasMode: DSP resource is used for playing/compressing announcement.

atmUniOperStatus.description: The operational status of the UNI: 'outOfService' means the UNI is out of service 'inService' means the UNI is in service

atmUniMyNeighborIpAddress.name: atmUniMyNeighborIpAddress
atmUniMyNeighborIpAddress.description: The IP address of the neighbor system connected to the far end of this interface, to which a Network Management Station can send SNMP messages, as IP datagrams sent to UDP port 161, in order to access network management information concerning the operation of that system. Note that the value of this object can currently only be obtained by manual configuration.

atmUniMyNeighborIfName.name: atmUniMyNeighborIfName
atmUniMyNeighborIfName.description: The textual name of the interface on the neighbor system on the far end of this interface, and to which this interface connects. If the neighbor system is manageable through SNMP and supports the object ifName, the value of this object must be identical with that of ifName for the ifEntry of the lowest level physical interface for this port. If this interface does not have a textual name, the value of this object is a zero length string. Note that the value of this object can currently only be obtained by manual configuration.

atmUniVpiSig.name: atmUniVpiSig
atmUniVpiSig.description: VPI value for the signalling channel for the UNI interface.

atmUniVciSig.name: atmUniVciSig
atmUniVciSig.description: VCI value for the signalling channel for the UNI interface.

atmUniVpiIlmi.name: atmUniVpiIlmi
atmUniVpiIlmi.description: VPI value for the ilmi channel for the UNI interface.

atmUniVciIlmi.name: atmUniVciIlmi
atmUniVciIlmi.description: VCI value for the ilmi channel for the UNI interface.

atmUniAtmSignalingStatus.name: atmUniAtmSignalingStatus
atmUniAtmSignalingStatus.description: Indicates if atm signaling is enabled or disabled for this interface.

atmUniMyIfName.name: atmUniMyIfName
atmUniMyIfName.description: A textual name of this interface. If this system is manageable manageable through SNMP and supports the object ifName, the value of this object must be identical with that of ifName for the ifEntry of the lowest level physical interface for this port. This interface must be uniquely named on this system to distinguish parallel links with a neighboring system. If this interface does not have a textual name, the value of this object is a zero length string.

atmUniIlmiProtocolStatus.name: atmUniIlmiProtocolStatus
atmUniIlmiProtocolStatus.description: The administrative status: 'enabled' - ILMI protocol enabled on UNI 'disabled' - ILMI protocol disabled on UNI.

atmUniIlmiOperStatus.name: atmUniIlmiOperStatus
atmUniIlmiOperStatus.description: The operational status: 'outOfService' - ILMI connectivity is down 'inService' - ILMI connectivity is up.

atmUniIlmiSecureLinkProc.name: atmUniIlmiSecureLinkProc

atmUniIlmiTimerS.name: atmUniIlmiTimerS
atmUniIlmiTimerS.description: Timer S (secs). Used to poll peer when link is down.

atmUniIlmiTimerT.name: atmUniIlmiTimerT

atmUniIlmiRetryK.name: atmUniIlmiRetryK

bridgePathCost.description: The contribution of this port to the path cost of paths towards the spanning tree root which include this port. 802-1D-1990 recommends that the default value of this parameter be in inverse proportion to the speed of the attached LAN.

bridgeDomainEntry.description: A table entry for a Bridge Domain on an ethernet card

bridgeDomainOperStatus.description: The operational status of the interface: 'outOfService' interface is out of service 'inService' interface is in service

bridgeDomainPriority.description: The value of the writeable portion of the Bridge ID, i.e., the first two octets of the (8 octet long) Bridge ID. The other (last) 6 octets of the Bridge ID are given by the value of dot1dBaseBridgeAddress.

bridgeDomainTimeSinceTopologyChange.name: bridgeDomainTimeSinceTopologyChange
bridgeDomainTimeSinceTopologyChange.description: The time (in hundredths of a second) since the last time a topology change was detedted by the bridge entity.

bridgeDomainDesignatedRoot.name: bridgeDomainDesignatedRoot
bridgeDomainDesignatedRoot.description: The bridge identifier of the root of the spanning tree as determined by the Spanning Tree Protocol as executed by this node. This value is used as the Root Identifier parameter in all Configuration Bridge PDUs originated by this node.

bridgeDomainRootCost.name: bridgeDomainRootCost
bridgeDomainRootCost.description: The cost of the path to the root as seen from this bridge.

bridgeDomainRootPort.name: bridgeDomainRootPort
bridgeDomainRootPort.description: The port number of the port which offers the lowest cost path from this bridge to the root bridge.

bridgeDomainMaxMessageAge.name: bridgeDomainMaxMessageAge
bridgeDomainMaxMessageAge.description: The maximum age of Spanning Tree Protocol information learned from the network on any port before it is discarded, in units of hundredths of a second. This is the actual value that this bridge is currently using.

bridgeDomainHelloTime.name: bridgeDomainHelloTime
bridgeDomainHelloTime.description: The amount of time between the transmission of Configuration bridge PDUs by this node on any port when it is the root of the spanning tree or trying to become so, in units of hundredths of a second. This is the actual value that this bridge is currently using.

bridgeDomainHoldTime.name: bridgeDomainHoldTime
bridgeDomainHoldTime.description: This time value determines the interval length during which no more than two Configuration bridge PDUs shall be transmitted by this node, in units of hundredths of a second.

bridgeDomainForwardDelay.name: bridgeDomainForwardDelay
bridgeDomainForwardDelay.description: This time value, measured in units of hundredths of a second, controls how fast a port changes its state. The value determines how long the port stays in each of the Listening and Learning states, which precede the Forwarding state. This value is also used, when a topology change has been detected and is underway, to age all dynamic entries in the Forwarding Database. [Note that this value is the one that this bridge is currently using, in contrast to bridgeDomainBridgeForwardDelay which is the value that this bridge and all others would start using if/when this bridge were to become the root.]

bridgeDomainMaxBridgeAge.name: bridgeDomainMaxBridgeAge
bridgeDomainMaxBridgeAge.description: The value that all bridges use for MaxAge when this bridge is acting as the root. Note that 802.1D-1990 specifies that the range for this parameter is related to the value of bridgeDomainBridgeHelloTime. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D-1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds.

bridgeDomainBridgeHelloTime.name: bridgeDomainBridgeHelloTime
bridgeDomainBridgeHelloTime.description: The value that all bridges use for HelloTime when this bridge is acting as the root. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D- 1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds.

bridgeDomainBridgeForwardDelay.name: bridgeDomainBridgeForwardDelay
bridgeDomainBridgeForwardDelay.description: The value that all bridges user for ForwardDelay when this bridge is acting as the root. Note that 802.1D-1990 specifies that the range for this parameter is related to the value of bridgeDomainMaxBridgeAge. The granularity of this timer is specified by 802.1D-1990 to be 1 second. An agent may return a badValue error if a set is attempted to a value which is not a whole number of seconds.

bridgeDomainAgingTime.name: bridgeDomainAgingTime
bridgeDomainAgingTime.description: The timeout period in seconds for aging out dynamically learned forwarding information. 802.1D-1990 recommends a default of 300 seconds.

bridgeDomainSpanningTree.name: bridgeDomainSpanningTree
bridgeDomainSpanningTree.description: Allows the bridge to be configured to run without the spanning tree algorithm.

bridgeDomainTopologyChanges.name: bridgeDomainTopologyChanges
bridgeDomainTopologyChanges.description: The total number of topology changes detected by this bridge since the management entity was last reset or initialized.

bridgeDomainLearnedEntryDiscards.name: bridgeDomainLearnedEntryDiscards
bridgeDomainLearnedEntryDiscards.description: The total number of Forwarding Database entries, which have been or would have been learnt, but have been discarded due to a lack of space to store them in the Forwarding Database. If this counter is increasing, it indicates that the Forwarding Database is regularly becoming full (a condition which has unpleasant performance effects on the subnetwork). If this counter has a significant value but is not presently increasing, it indicates that the problem has been occurring but is not persistent.

atmPvcVccConnectionStatus.name: atmPvcVccConnectionStatus
atmPvcVccConnectionStatus.description: Indicates the current connections status. Active: All interfaces through which the connection is going are in service. Inactive: One of the end interfaces of the connection is not in service. The rest of the states apply to connections going through resource interfaces like DSP2 and FEC. These interfaces are dynamically allocated. InactiveA2B-B2A: Both the A2B and B2A resource interfaces are not in service. InactiveA2B: The A2B resource interface is not in service. InactiveB2A: The B2A resource interface is not in service. If an end interface and the resource interfaces are out of service, the status will be inactive because the end interfaces take priority.

atmPvcVccOamStatus.name: atmPvcVccOamStatus
atmPvcVccOamStatus.description: Indicates the OAM monitoring status of side A. The 5 possible states are: Unsupp: No monitoring enabled. End-Pt: A side is only an end point, therefore it will respond to AIS/RDI. Seg-Pt: A side is only a segment point, therefore it will only respond to maintenance OAM cells and not fault cells. End-Seg-Pt: A side is both an end point and a segment point. Intermediate-Pt: It will only generate AIS during local failure. For ATM-to-ATM connections the OAM status will be symmetric on both sides of the connection.

atmPvcVccViB.name: atmPvcVccViB

atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeA2B.name: atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeA2B
atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeA2B.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one_bucket_notag_0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two_bucket_notag_0plus1_0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two_bucket_notag_0plus1_0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two_bucket_tag_0plus1_0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best_effort_tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A.name: atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A
atmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one_bucket_notag_0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two_bucket_notag_0plus1_0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two_bucket_notag_0plus1_0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two_bucket_tag_0plus1_0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best_effort_tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

atmPvcVpcConnectionStatus.name: atmPvcVpcConnectionStatus
atmPvcVpcConnectionStatus.description: Indicates the current connections status. Active: All interfaces through which the connection is going are in service. Inactive: One of the end interfaces of the connection is not in service. The rest of the states apply to connections going through resource interfaces like DSP2 and FEC. These interfaces are dynamically allocated. InactiveA2B-B2A: Both the A2B and B2A resource interfaces are not in service. InactiveA2B: The A2B resource interface is not in service. InactiveB2A: The B2A resource interface is not in service. If an end interface and the resource interfaces are out of service, the status will be inactive because the end interfaces take priority.

atmPvcVpcOamStatus.name: atmPvcVpcOamStatus
atmPvcVpcOamStatus.description: Indicates the OAM monitoring status of side A. The 5 possible states are: Unsupp: No monitoring enabled. End-Pt: A side is only an end point, therefore it will respond to AIS/RDI. Seg-Pt: A side is only a segment point, therefore it will only respond to maintenance OAM cells and not fault cells. End-Seg-Pt: A side is both an end point and a segment point. Intermediate-Pt: It will only generate AIS during local failure. For ATM-to-ATM connections the OAM status will be symmetric on both sides of the connection.

atmPvcVpcCnfrmTypeA2B.name: atmPvcVpcCnfrmTypeA2B
atmPvcVpcCnfrmTypeA2B.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one-bucket-notag-0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

cirEmAtmPvcVccConnectionStatus.name: cirEmAtmPvcVccConnectionStatus
cirEmAtmPvcVccConnectionStatus.description: Indicates the current connections status. Active: All interfaces through which the connection is going are in service. Inactive: One of the end interfaces of the connection is not in service. The rest of the states apply to connections going through resource interfaces like DSP2 and FEC. These interfaces are dynamically allocated. InactiveA2B-B2A: Both the A2B and B2A resource interfaces are not in service. InactiveA2B: The A2B resource interface is not in service. InactiveB2A: The B2A resource interface is not in service. If an end interface and the resource interfaces are out of service, the status will be inactive because the end interfaces take priority.

cirEmAtmPvcVccViB.name: cirEmAtmPvcVccViB

cirEmAtmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A.name: cirEmAtmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A
cirEmAtmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one-bucket-notag-0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

bridgeAtmPvcVccCnfrmTypeB2A.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one-bucket-notag-0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

frAtmSpvcVccServiceType.name: frAtmSpvcVccServiceType
frAtmSpvcVccServiceType.description: service type, Frame relay traffic is carried by VBR type of service only.

frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenIn.name: frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenIn
frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenIn.description: The time interval over which CIR and the burst sizes (Bc and Be) are measured in the A2B direction. The unit is milliseconds.

frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenOut.name: frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenOut
frAtmSpvcVccTimeLenOut.description: The time interval over which CIR and the burst sizes (Bc and Be) are measured in the A2B direction. The unit is milliseconds.

frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateA2B.name: frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateA2B
frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateA2B.description: Peak cell rate - side A, in cells per second, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateA2B.name: frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateA2B
frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateA2B.description: Sustained cell rate - side A, in cells per second, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeA2B.name: frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeA2B
frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeA2B.description: Maximum burst size - side A, in cells, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateB2A.name: frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateB2A
frAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateB2A.description: Peak cell rate - side B, in cells per second, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateB2A.name: frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateB2A
frAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateB2A.description: Sustained cell rate - side B, in cells per second, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeB2A.name: frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeB2A
frAtmSpvcVccMaxBurstSizeB2A.description: Maximum burst size - side B, in cells, this will reflect the frame relay parameters in atm terms.

frAtmSpvcVccConnType.name: frAtmSpvcVccConnType
frAtmSpvcVccConnType.description: The type of connection: activeSvc - attempt calls, whenever not established; passiveSvc - accepts calls

frAtmSpvcVccOperStatus.name: frAtmSpvcVccOperStatus
frAtmSpvcVccOperStatus.description: other - none of the types specified below; establishmentInProgress - connection is not operational, but call attempts are ongoing; connected - connection is currently operational; retriesExhausted - retry limit has been reached and call attempts have ceased; noAddressSupplied - no remote address has been configured, so no call attempts are initiated; lowerLayerDown - SPVC handler is not operational.

frAtmSpvcVccRemoteFrPortAddr.name: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteFrPortAddr
frAtmSpvcVccRemoteFrPortAddr.description: The ATM address supporting the corresponding far end FR IWF process. If no address is supplied, no attempts to establish the active SVC are initiated.

frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType.name: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType
frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType.description: Indicates whether the remote DLCI/VPI/VCI values are to be used at the destination. If 'any' is used, the destination switch will choose the DLCI/VPI/VCI values. In such a case, once the SPVC is connected, the value of this object will change to 'required', such that the same DLCI/VPI/VCI values will continue to be used even if the connection is torn down and re-established. If the value 'required' is specified, the values: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteDlci or frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi and frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci, must be supplied and are used at the destination.

frAtmSpvcVccRemoteDlci.name: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteDlci
frAtmSpvcVccRemoteDlci.description: DLCI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VCC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 4095. If frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi.name: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi
frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi.description: VPI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VCC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 4095. If frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci.name: frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci
frAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci.description: VCI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VCC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 65535. If frAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

frAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval.name: frAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval
frAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval.description: The time to wait before attempting to establish the SVC after previous failed call attempt. 0 indicates retry will be attempted immediately.

frAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit.name: frAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit
frAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit.description: A maximum limit on how many retries. 0 indicates no limit.

frAtmSpvcVccRestart.name: frAtmSpvcVccRestart
frAtmSpvcVccRestart.description: restart, the active SVC is released if necessary and a new setup procedure is begun; or noop

frAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure.name: frAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure
frAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure.description: Indicates how many attempts to establish the connection have failed. It is reset whenever a connection is successfully established or the SVC is restarted.

frAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause.name: frAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause
frAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause.description: CAUSE field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

frAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag.name: frAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag
frAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag.description: DIAGNOSTICS field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

frAtmSpvcVccRelease.name: frAtmSpvcVccRelease
frAtmSpvcVccRelease.description: Release the connnection established on the endpoint and if the endpoint is Active, do not retry.

atmAtmSpvcVccPeakCellRateA2B.description: Peak cell rate - side A, ATM port, in cells per second.

atmAtmSpvcVccSusCellRateB2A.description: Sustained cell rate - side B, ATM trunk, in cells per second.

atmAtmSpvcVccLeafReference.description: An arbitrary integer which serves to distinguish the mulitple leaves attached to a root of a point-to-multipoint SPVC. If point-to-point SPVC, the value should be 1.

atmAtmSpvcVccOperStatus.name: atmAtmSpvcVccOperStatus
atmAtmSpvcVccOperStatus.description: The operation status of the connection: other - none of the types specified below. establishmentInProgress - connection is not operational, but call attempts are ongoing. connected - connection is currently operational. retriesExhausted - retry limit has been reached and call attempts have ceased. noAddressSupplied - no remote address has been configured, so no call attempts are initiated. lowerLayerDown - SPVC handler is not operational.

atmAtmSpvcVccRowStatus.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRowStatus
atmAtmSpvcVccRowStatus.description: Used to create and delete a soft PVC. When this object is set to 'active', an attempt is made to set up the soft PVC. When this object has the value 'active' and is set to another value, any setup or connection in-progress is released.

atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType
atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType.description: Indicates whether the remote VPI/VCI values are to be used at the destination. If 'any' is used, the destination switch will choose the VPI/VCI values. In such a case, once the SPVC is connected, the value of this object will change to 'required', such that the same VPI/VCI values will continue to be used even if the connection is torn down and re-established. If the value 'required' is specified, the values: atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi and atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci, must be supplied and are used at the destination.

atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi
atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVpi.description: VPI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VCC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 4095. If atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci
atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteVci.description: VCI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VCC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 65535. If atmAtmSpvcVccRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

atmAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval
atmAtmSpvcVccRetryInterval.description: The time to wait before attempting to establish the SVC after a previous failed call attempt. A value of 0 indicates retries will be attempted immediately.

atmAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit
atmAtmSpvcVccRetryLimit.description: A maximum limit on how many retries should be attempted. A value of 0 indicates no limit.

atmAtmSpvcVccRestart.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRestart
atmAtmSpvcVccRestart.description: The active SVC is released, if necessary, and a new setup procedure is begun if 'restart', otherwise, noop.

atmAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure
atmAtmSpvcVccRetryFailure.description: Indicates how many attempts to establish the connection have failed. It it reset whenever a connection is successfully established or the SVC is restarted.

atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause.name: atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause
atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseCause.description: CAUSE field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag.name: atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag
atmAtmSpvcVccReleaseDiag.description: DIAGNOSTICS field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

atmAtmSpvcVccRelease.name: atmAtmSpvcVccRelease
atmAtmSpvcVccRelease.description: Release the connnection established on the endpoint and if the endpoint is Active, do not retry.

aal2TrunkConfigConnectionStatus.name: aal2TrunkConfigConnectionStatus
aal2TrunkConfigConnectionStatus.description: Indicates the current connections status. Active: All interfaces through which the connection is going are in service. Inactive: One of the end interfaces of the connection is not in service. The rest of the states apply to connections going through resource interfaces like DSP2 and FEC. These interfaces are dynamically allocated . InactiveA2B-B2A: Both the A2B and B2A resource interfaces are not in service. InactiveA2B: The A2B resource interface is not in service. InactiveB2A: The B2A resource interface is not in service. If an end interface and the resource interfaces are out of service, the status will be inactive because the end interfaces take priority.

aal2TrunkConfigViB.description: VI to associate the Egress part of the A2B connection .

aal2TrunkConfigCnfrmTypeB2A.name: aal2TrunkConfigCnfrmTypeB2A
aal2TrunkConfigCnfrmTypeB2A.description: The following is the description of this field This will be used in conjunction with the service type field to get the correct traffic behaviour. In the conformances the the 0 or 0plus1 refers to the clp bit in the cells. If 0plus1 is the bucket reference then the clp bit is ignored. If 0 is specified for the bucket then check only clp=0 cells. 1: Best Effort will try to send all cellsin a best effort way. This will follow the Aqueman Algorithm 2: one-bucket-notag-0plus1 will use 1 bucket i.e is the PCR(0+1) bucket and drop all cells in excess. 3: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0plus1 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0+1). All cells conforming to both buckets will be passed through. The rest will be dropped. 4: two-bucket-notag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which conform to both buckets are passed through. The rest are dropped. 5: two-bucket-tag-0plus1-0 uses 2 buckets. The 2 buckets are pcr(0+1) and scr(0) or pcr(0). Cells which do not conform to the first bucket are dropped. Cells which do not conform to the 2nd bucket are tagged. 6: best-effort-tag. Tag all cells and then do a best effort.

aal2TrunkConfigOamStatus.name: aal2TrunkConfigOamStatus
aal2TrunkConfigOamStatus.description: Indicates the OAM monitoring status of side A. The 2 possible states are: Unsupp: No monitoring enabled. End-Pt: Atm side is only an end point, therefore it will respond to AIS/RDI. End-Seg-Pt: A side is both an end point and a segment point.

aal2TrunkCuTimer.name: aal2TrunkCuTimer
aal2TrunkCuTimer.description: CuTimer represents 'combined use timer', is set to zero such that every ATM cell transmitted contains one, and only one, AAL2 packet, and the first octet of the AAL2 packet header follows immediately after the Start Field in the ATM cell payload. If the AAL2 packet payload is less than 44 octets, the remainder of the ATM cell payload following the end of the AAL2 packet shall be filled with zeros as padding. Each increment of CuTimer means 5ms more to wait. And cuTimer default value 4 means to wait 20ms before the ATM cell is sent out.

atmAtmSpvcVpcOperStatus.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcOperStatus
atmAtmSpvcVpcOperStatus.description: The operation status of the connection: other - none of the types specified below. establishmentInProgress - connection is not operational, but call attempts are ongoing. connected - connection is currently operational. retriesExhausted - retry limit has been reached and call attempts have ceased. noAddressSupplied - no remote address has been configured, so no call attempts are initiated. lowerLayerDown - SPVC handler is not operational.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRowStatus.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRowStatus
atmAtmSpvcVpcRowStatus.description: Used to create and delete a soft PVC. When this object is set to 'active', an attempt is made to set up the soft PVC. When this object has the value 'active' and is set to another value, any setup or connection in-progress is released.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteSelectType.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteSelectType
atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteSelectType.description: Indicates whether the remote VPI values are to be used at the destination. If 'any' is used, the destination switch will choose the VPI values. In such a case, once the SPVC is connected, the value of this object will change to 'required', such that the same VPI values will continue to be used even if the connection is torn down and re-established. If the value 'required' is specified, the values: atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteVpi and must be supplied and are used at the destination.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteVpi.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteVpi
atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteVpi.description: VPI value to be used at the destination of an ATM SPVC VPC connection. Valid range is a number between 0 and 4095. If atmAtmSpvcVpcRemoteSelectType is configured as 'any', then this value is not relevant.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryInterval.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryInterval
atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryInterval.description: The time to wait before attempting to establish the SVC after a previous failed call attempt. A value of 0 indicates retries will be attempted immediately.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryLimit.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryLimit
atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryLimit.description: A maximum limit on how many retries should be attempted. A value of 0 indicates no limit.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRestart.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRestart
atmAtmSpvcVpcRestart.description: The active SVC is released, if necessary, and a new setup procedure is begun if 'restart', otherwise, noop.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryFailure.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryFailure
atmAtmSpvcVpcRetryFailure.description: Indicates how many attempts to establish the connection have failed. It it reset whenever a connection is successfully established or the SVC is restarted.

atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseCause.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseCause
atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseCause.description: CAUSE field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseDiag.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseDiag
atmAtmSpvcVpcReleaseDiag.description: DIAGNOSTICS field value of the last RELEASE message received for this SVC.

atmAtmSpvcVpcRelease.name: atmAtmSpvcVpcRelease
atmAtmSpvcVpcRelease.description: Release the connnection established on the endpoint and if the endpoint is Active, do not retry.

ethernetPortStatsEntry.name: ethernetPortStatsEntry
ethernetPortStatsEntry.description: Statistics for a particular interface to an ethernet-like medium.

ethernetPortStatsId.name: ethernetPortStatsId
ethernetPortStatsId.description: An index value that uniquely identifies an interface to an ethernet-like medium. The interface identified by a particular value of this index is the same interface as identified by the same value of ethernetPortId.

ethernetPortStatsTimer.name: ethernetPortStatsTimer
ethernetPortStatsTimer.description: Time, in seconds, since last reset.

ethernetPortStatsAlignmentErrors.name: ethernetPortStatsAlignmentErrors
ethernetPortStatsAlignmentErrors.description: A count of frames received on a particular interface that are not an integral number of octets in length and do not pass the FCS check. The count represented by an instance of this object is incremented when the alignmentError status is returned by the MAC service to the LLC (or other MAC user). Received frames for which multiple error conditions obtain are, according to the conventions of IEEE 802.3 Layer Management, counted exclusively according to the error status presented to the LLC.

ethernetPortStatsFCSErrors.name: ethernetPortStatsFCSErrors
ethernetPortStatsFCSErrors.description: A count of frames received on a particular interface that are an integral number of octets in length but do not pass the FCS check. The count represented by an instance of this object is incremented when the frameCheckError status is returned by the MAC service to the LLC (or other MAC user). Received frames for which multiple error conditions obtain are, according to the conventions of IEEE 802.3 Layer Management, counted exclusively according to the error status presented to the LLC.

ethernetPortStatsSingleCollisionFrames.name: ethernetPortStatsSingleCollisionFrames
ethernetPortStatsSingleCollisionFrames.description: A count of successfully transmitted frames on a particular interface for which trnasmission is inhibited by exactly one collision. A frame that is counted by an instance of this object is also counted by the corresponding instance of either the ifOutUcastPkts, IfOutMulticastPkts, or ifOutBroadcastPkts, and is not counted by the corresponding instance of the ethernetPortStatsMulitipleCollisionFrames object.

ethernetPortStatsMultipleCollisionFrames.name: ethernetPortStatsMultipleCollisionFrames
ethernetPortStatsMultipleCollisionFrames.description: A count of successfully transmitted frames on a particular interface for which trnasmission is inhibited by more than one collision. A frame that is counted by an instance of this object is also counted by the corresponding instance of either the ifOutUcastPkts, IfOutMulticastPkts, or ifOutBroadcastPkts, and is not counted by the corresponding instance of the ethernetPortStatsSingleCollisionFrames object.

ethernetPortStatsSQETestErrors.name: ethernetPortStatsSQETestErrors
ethernetPortStatsSQETestErrors.reference: ANSI/IEEE Std 802.3-1985 Carrier Sense Multiple Access with Collision Detection Access Method and Physical Layer Specifications
ethernetPortStatsSQETestErrors.description: A count of times that the SQE TEST ERROR message is generated by the PLS sublayer for a particular interface. The SQE TEST ERROR message is defined in section 7.2.2.2.4 of ANSI/IEEE 802.3-1985 and its generation is described in section 7.2.4.6 of the same document.

ethernetPortStatsDeferredTransmissions.name: ethernetPortStatsDeferredTransmissions
ethernetPortStatsDeferredTransmissions.description: A count of frames for which the first transmission attempt on a particluar interface is delayed because the medium is busy. the count represented by an instance of this object does not include frames involved in collisions.

ethernetPortStatsLateCollisions.name: ethernetPortStatsLateCollisions
ethernetPortStatsLateCollisions.description: The number of times that a collision is detected on a particular interface later than 512 bit-times into the transmission of a packet. Five hundred and twelve bit-times corresponds to 51.2 microseconds on a 10 Mbit/s system. A (late) collision included in a count represented by an instance of this object is also considered as a (generic) collision for purposes of other collision-related statistics.

ethernetPortStatsExcessiveCollisions.name: ethernetPortStatsExcessiveCollisions
ethernetPortStatsExcessiveCollisions.description: A count of frames for which transmission on a particular interface fails due to excessive collisions.

ethernetPortStatsInternalMacTransmitErro.name: ethernetPortStatsInternalMacTransmitErrors
ethernetPortStatsInternalMacTransmitErro.description: A count of frames for which transmission on a particular interface fails due to an internal MAC sublayer transmit error. A frame is only counted by an instance of this object if it is not counted by the corresponding instance of either the ethernetPortStatsLateCollisions object, the ethernetPortStatsExcessiveCollisions object, or the ethernetPortStatsCarrierSenseErrors object. The precise meaning of the count represented by an instance of this object is implementation- specific. In particular, an instance of this object may represent a count of transmission errors on a particular interface that are not otherwise counted.

ethernetPortStatsCarrierSenseErrors.name: ethernetPortStatsCarrierSenseErrors
ethernetPortStatsCarrierSenseErrors.description: The number of times that the carrier sense condition was lost or never asserted when attempting to transmit a frame on a particular interface. The count represented by an instance of this object is incremented at most once per transmission attempt, even if the carrier sense condition fluctuates during a transmission attempt.

ethernetPortStatsFrameTooLongs.name: ethernetPortStatsFrameTooLongs
ethernetPortStatsFrameTooLongs.description: A count of frames received on a particular interface that exceed the maximum permitted frame size. The count represented by an instance of this object is incremented when the frameTooLong status is returned by the MAC service to the LLC (or other MAC user). Received frames for which multiple error conditions obtain are, according to the conventions of IEEE 802.3 Layer Management, counted exclusively according to the error status presented to the LLC.

ethernetPortStatsInternalMacReceiveError.name: ethernetPortStatsInternalMacReceiveErrors
ethernetPortStatsInternalMacReceiveError.description: A count of frames for which reception on a particular interface fails due to an internal MAC sublayer receive error. A frame is only counted by an instance of this object if it is not counted by the corresponding instance of either the ethernetPortStatsFrameTooLongs object, the ethernetPortStatsAlignmentErrors object, or the ethernetPortStatsFCSErrors object. The precise meaning of the count represented by an instance of this object is implementation- specific. In particular, an instance of this object may represent a count of receive errors on a particular interface that are not otherwise counted.

bridgeStatsBasePortDelayExceededDiscards.description: The number of frames discarded by this port due to excessive transit delay through the bridge. It is incremented by both transparent and source route bridges. High-order 32 bits.

bridgeStatsBasePortDelayExceededDiscards.name: bridgeStatsBasePortDelayExceededDiscardsLo
bridgeStatsBasePortDelayExceededDiscards.description: The number of frames discarded by this port due to excessive transit delay through the bridge. It is incremented by both transparent and source route bridges. Low-order 32 bits.

bridgeStatsBasePortMtuExceededDiscardsHi.name: bridgeStatsBasePortMtuExceededDiscardsHi

bridgeStatsBasePortMtuExceededDiscardsLo.name: bridgeStatsBasePortMtuExceededDiscardsLo

bridgeStatsTpPortInFramesHi.name: bridgeStatsTpPortInFramesHi
bridgeStatsTpPortInFramesHi.description: The number of frames that have been received by this port from its segment. Note that a frame received on the interface corresponding to this port is only counted by this object if and only if it is for a protocol being processed by the local bridging function, including bridge management frames. High-order 32 bits.

bridgeStatsTpPortInFramesLo.name: bridgeStatsTpPortInFramesLo

Note that a frame received on the interface corresponding to this port is only counted by this object if and only if it is for a protocol being processed by the local bridging function, including bridge management frames.
